## Eukaryotic Transcription

[Eukaryotic transcription](/Eukaryotic_transcription) is the elaborate process that [eukaryotic](/Eukaryote) cells employ to meticulously copy the genetic information, which is so carefully stored within their [DNA](/DNA), into manageable units of transportable, [complementary](/Complementarity_(molecular_biology)) [RNA](/RNA) replicas. This isn't merely a biological function; it's a testament to the evolutionary imperative for highly controlled and adaptable gene expression. While the fundamental act of [gene transcription](/Transcription_(biology)) is shared by both eukaryotic and [prokaryotic](/Prokaryotic) cells, the eukaryotic approach is, predictably, far more convoluted.

Unlike the relatively versatile [prokaryotic RNA polymerase](/Bacterial_transcription) that initiates the transcription of all different types of [RNA](/RNA) with a singular catalytic entity, [RNA polymerase](/RNA_polymerase) in eukaryotes (humans included, naturally) has diversified into three distinct variations. Each of these specialized polymerases is tasked with translating a specific class of gene, a division of labor that speaks volumes about the increased demands placed on eukaryotic genomes. Furthermore, a defining characteristic of eukaryotic cells is the presence of a [nucleus](/Cell_nucleus), a membrane-bound organelle that physically segregates the processes of transcription (which occurs within the nucleus) from [translation](/Translation_(biology)) (which takes place in the [cytoplasm](/Cytoplasm)). This spatial separation allows for additional layers of regulatory control, ensuring that only fully processed and approved [RNA](/RNA) transcripts venture forth to direct protein synthesis.

Within the confines of the eukaryotic [nucleus](/Cell_nucleus), the [DNA](/DNA) is not merely free-floating; it is intricately packaged into compact structures known as [nucleosomes](/Nucleosomes) and even higher-order [chromatin](/Chromatin) architectures. This dense packaging, while essential for genome organization, inherently creates barriers to the transcriptional machinery, necessitating a sophisticated array of mechanisms to grant access to specific genes at precise times. Consequently, the sheer scale and complexity of the eukaryotic [genome](/Genome) demand an equally vast and intricate system for controlling [gene expression](/Regulation_of_gene_expression).

The journey of [eukaryotic transcription](/Eukaryotic_transcription) unfolds in three distinct and sequential stages: [initiation](/Transcription_initiation), [elongation](/Transcription_elongation), and [termination](/Transcription_termination). Each phase is a carefully choreographed ballet of molecular interactions, ensuring fidelity and regulation at every turn.

The diverse [RNAs](/RNA) produced through these processes serve a multitude of critical cellular functions. For instance, the structural components that form the [ribosome](/Ribosome)—the cell's protein synthesis factory—are transcribed by [RNA polymerase I](/RNA_polymerase_I). Meanwhile, the genes encoding proteins, the workhorses of the cell, are transcribed by [RNA polymerase II](/RNA_polymerase_II) into [messenger RNAs](/MRNA) ([mRNAs](/MRNA)). These [mRNAs](/MRNA) then dutifully carry the vital information from the [DNA](/DNA) out of the [nucleus](/Cell_nucleus) to the designated sites of protein synthesis in the [cytoplasm](/Cytoplasm). Intriguingly, it's not the protein-coding [mRNAs](/MRNA) that dominate the transcriptional output; rather, the so-called [non-coding RNAs](/Non-coding_RNA) account for the vast majority of a cell's transcriptional activity. These [non-coding RNAs](/Non-coding_RNA), despite not leading to protein production, perform a wide variety of absolutely critical cellular functions, from gene regulation to structural roles.

## RNA polymerase

Main article: [RNA polymerase §&#160;Eukaryotes](/RNA_polymerase)

Eukaryotes, in their relentless pursuit of specialization, possess not one, but three distinct nuclear [RNA polymerases](/RNA_polymerase). Each of these enzymes has been assigned its own unique set of responsibilities and exhibits specific properties, a testament to the eukaryotic cell's commitment to avoiding unnecessary versatility.

